canonical:
  title: 謝東京賜錢宴表
  author: 金克己
  language: lzh
  text: 復我邦家戒王程於鱗隰送以禮樂張祖席於翼京榮幸非常感驚罔極中謝 陪臣奉章脩聘成命告歸海域遄行雖返旆鰈墟之表天庭結戀尙懸旌螭陛之前豈謂皇帝德不遺微仁先厚往降綸言於北闕宣綺宴於東都徒御增輝道塗聳覩有始有卒深感聖人之恩無期無疆仰祈君子之壽
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 謝東京賜錢宴表
  author: 金克己
  language: lzh
  text: 復我邦家。戒王程於鱗隰。送以禮樂。張祖席於翼京。榮幸非常。感驚罔極。中謝。 陪臣奉章脩聘。成命告歸。海域遄行。雖返旆鰈墟之表。天庭結戀。尙懸旌螭陛之前。豈謂皇帝德不遺微。仁先厚往。降綸言於北闕。宣綺宴於東都。徒御增輝。道塗聳覩。有始有卒。深感聖人之恩。無期無疆。仰祈君子之壽。
korean:
  title: 동경에서 전송연을 주심을 사례하는 표
  author: 김극기
  language: kor
  text: |-
    본국으로 돌아가려고 왕정(王程 왕명(王命)으로 가는 여정(旅程))을 원습(原隰 사신의 행로)으로 출발하옵던 차, 예악(禮樂)을 보내시어 동경(東京)에서 전송연을 차려 주시오니, 영행(榮幸)이 비상하온지라, 감격하고 놀람이 그지없도소이다. 중사(中謝)
    배신이 표(表)를 받들어 빙례(聘禮)를 닦고서 사명을 이루고 돌아갈 때, 해역(海域)으로 빨리 오니 비록 첩역(鰈域 한국)으로 깃발을 돌리오나 천정(天庭)이 못내 그리워 마음이 아직 이폐(螭陛) 앞에 있사온대, 뜻밖에도 황제께옵서 덕은 미천(微賤)한 자를 빠뜨리지 않으시고 인(仁)은 가는 자를 후히 하시는 데 먼저 하시어 북궐(北闕)에서는 윤음(綸音)을 내리시고 동도(東都)에서는 화려한 잔치를 차려 주시오니, 하인들까지 빛이 더 나오며 연로(沿路)의 사람들이 모두 구경하옵나이다. 처음부터 끝까지 돌봐 주시는 성인(聖人)의 은혜에 깊이 감격하오며, 기한이 없고 끝이 없는 군자(君子)의 수(壽)를 우러러 비옵나이다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0390_010_0030&viewSync=OT
  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Memorial of Gratitude for the Farewell Banquet Bestowed at the Eastern Capital
  author: Kim Geuk-gi
  language: eng
  text: |-
    My sovereign lord has restored my homeland, guiding my steps through the fields toward his royal command. Yet before my departure, you graced me with ritual and music, arranging a lavish feast within the Eastern Capital's walls. Such extraordinary honor overwhelms my heart with gratitude beyond measure.

    As a humble envoy bearing my sovereign's credentials, I completed the ceremonial mission and turned toward home. Swift was my journey across the sea, yet though my banner retreated toward distant shores, my spirit lingered still before the dragon-adorned steps of the celestial court. How could I have foreseen such imperial benevolence? Your Majesty's virtue forgets not the lowly, your compassion blesses those who depart. From the Northern Palace flows your imperial word; in the Eastern Capital, brilliant banquets are laid. Even my servants are crowned with reflected glory, and all along the road speak of what they witnessed. From beginning to end, you have sustained me with the grace of a sage—immeasurable, boundless. I raise my hands in reverent prayer for your eternal longevity, noble lord.
  footnotes:
    - This is a state memorial (표, pyo) of thanks presented by a Korean envoy to the Chinese imperial court, likely during the Goryeo period when such diplomatic missions were frequent.
    - The 'Eastern Capital' (東京, Dongjing) refers to Kaifeng, the northern Song capital, emphasizing the distance and grandeur of the honor bestowed.
    - The contrast between the envoy's distant 'homeland' and lingering affection for the imperial court reflects the complex hierarchical relationship between tributary state and suzerain power.
